..Party Report starts here..

Another  thing you may like to know,  that like the Maggie party,  there 
was a realtime article produced..  No, not just the Diskbusters Realtime 
article,  a  Fried Bits/Symposium tradition,  but one written on pen and 
paper  by ourselves,  which sort of came from nowhere,  or Tat's pad and 
paper to be totally precise..  Like the Maggie party review, this report 
will  be intercut with choice bits of realtime article,  until it is all 
used up.. So there..

Thursday 4th April, 7.30 am (GMT) (DAY ONE)

A  faint wafting of Radio Four in a news and currenty  affairs  attitude 
waves away the sleep from your narrator..  I stay glued to the bed until 
7.39 when I finally convince me to get up,  as doing the breakfast thing 
might be quite a good idea..  As things turn out over the next 36 hours, 
it later transpires that it is a very very good idea indeed..

8.20am..  Start  the  drive  to Felice's place twenty miles away  in  St 
Neots,  where  we are to meet and travel to the railway station for  the 
train  to  London..  A momentary fit of false paranoia has me turn  back 
home  whilst still embattled in Rushden morning traffic,  but I did  not 
forget anything after all.. About ten minutes added to the journey, nice 
one!!

Shortly after 9am..  Arrive at Felice's place, dodging past a JCB digger 
and several men laying a new pavement,  park car, nervously wondering if 
it  is  going  to become part of the building  works  going  on  nearby, 
remember  that double bank holiday of Good Friday and Easter Monday  are 
to  follow after today,  and figure out that my car will probably be  ok 
after all,  smile.. Felice is waiting in his hallway with two large bags 
packed  and ready to go..  Our taxi is due at 9.30 which still gives  us 
time to view the Symposium Invite intro, very nice it is too.. 

The Taxi is a little late and we overhear cursing on the intercom as  it 
transpires  that this car is a different one from the one  allocated  to 
pick us up, the previous driver having gotten a little bit lost..

10.05am..  St  Neots  railway  station,  an undistinguised waiting  room 
smelling of tramps wee is vacated as Maggie Team and several middle-aged 
American Women board the train for London.. American Women are unsure if 
we have invaded first class carriage until Maggie Editor points out that 
first  class accomodations can only be distinguished from  second  class 
seating  by the fact that first class has cigar,  rather than  cigarette 
burns on the carpet.. 

An  hour  later..  Get off at Finsbury Park,  a small station near Kings 
Cross..  Travel  on  London  Underground  Victoria Line  on  dodgy  non-
underground  travelling  British Rail/Network  Southeast  tickets  which 
Felice think are ok, probably.. Maggie editor starts to sweat a bit.. 

Arrive  at  London  Victoria..  Tickets NOT ok after all,  but  friendly 
station  official accepts our garbled explanation and lets us out  after 
paying the normal fare..  We wait awhile at Victoria,  hoping to pick up 
some  other party visitors,  after trips to W.H.Smith to stock up on the 
new issues of 'Viz Magazine' and 'Private Eye',  visits to the Bureau de 
Change  to convert the last of my cash to Deutschmarks,  and some  quick 
sidestepping  to  avoid the woman trying to sell  us  'lucky  heather'.. 
Eventually give up waiting here as a bad job, and decide to do some more 
concentrated waiting at Victoria Coach Station instead..

After some initially faulty signposted directions which nearly put us on 
to  the platform for the 12.20 for Ruislip,  we reach the coach  station 
after  a reasonable walk ('reasonable' without bags and  suitcases  that 
is..)  The entrance foyer contains a waiting Tat who is  guarding  Leons 
bags as well..  Leon (Mr Pink) turns up shortly after with the news that 
the  toilets here cost an extortionate twenty pence to use..  Resolve to 
hold  on to bladder until we reach the Cross Channel Ferry..  We are  to 
meet  Mike Noyce,  Kev 'Taffy' Davies,  and another Falcon person called 
Neil (Rodway-Jones),  sometimes signed as Arnel in the realtime, who was 
been  in touch with Tat through the IRC,  but not met in person as yet.. 
We move to the waiting area for the coach, and happily find all of these 
people there already waiting..

Long  wait  ensues until coach puts its face around the  corner..  Large 
numbers of Danish students pile up erratically in the waiting area, with 
odd  shaped packages and guitars tied up with string..  Eurolines (Hell-
Coaches  Incorporated) checking-in desk remains closed  and  shuttered.. 

We  stand  absently on one leg for a while until  the  check-in  counter 
opens..  After a while, we are let through reluctantly, and wait for the 
coach  which is sat sullenly in the station with an 'I've  broken  down' 
expression  written  all  over it..  Maggie Editor goes to stock  up  on 
(very)  large chocolate bar,  sandwiches (eaten 0.00065 seconds  later, 
and  bottle of coke (drunk in various places on and off the coach.)  The 
coach arrives, unbroken down at last, and a mad panic to get luggage and 
bodies on ensues..  We don't end up all together, but in a group of four 
(Me,  Leon,  Felice and Neil),  Kev Davies and Mike Noyce together,  and 
poor old Tat all on his own!

About 3.30pm GMT.. Coach sets off at last, hurrah!

It  is quite a warm day,  especially in the greenhouse-like interior  of 
the upper deck of the coach.. The driver, fresh from loading the luggage 
sounds  like he is on the edge of a heart attack as he  announces  where 
the coach is going..  Breath, pause, speech, breath, pause, speech etc.. 
I  am sharing the seat with a Swedish Student who is mostly asleep,  but 
pass the time talking to Neil sitting just across the aisle..  Also Leon 
and  Felice  join  in..  The coach moves very slowly across  a  traffic-
stuffed London, and we wonder if we will ever make the Symposium.. 

No  worries  as  we make good time to Dover,  the coach wanders  in  the 
direction of the ferry boarding point,  and after a tense ten or fifteen 
minutes,  up  the ramp we go!  A quick dash for (free!) toilets follows, 
then the slower and more considered search for the bar..  Several drinks 
later (one per team member only!) and we are sitting comfortably for the 
first,  and probably only time on the trip.. Then the ferry lurches away 
from  the  quay,  we  kiss goodbye to good old Dover and  British  soil, 
facing  the  uncertainties of the next few days properly for  the  first 
time..

A  pad  of  paper makes an appearance,  courtesy of Tat,  and  having  a 
reputation for this sort of thing,  yours truly is appointed guardian of 
the  Maggie Symposium Realtime Article,  and the first entries are  made 
about this time..
 
