It does get better later, honest!

The  ferry  turns out to be one of the best bits of the  trip,  time  to 
stretch out,  relax,  wander around a bit.. Wander around very carefully 
as  the  floor does not seem to be in quite the same place  twice..  Try 
going  'outside' where a howling gale (thanks to the forward  motion  of 
the  ship)  is  blowing..  The evening sky has a  lovely  misty  effect, 
nothing else is visible,  apart from a few lonely sounding seagulls, and 
the distant smudged shape of another ferry ahead of us..

About  fifteen minutes towards the end,  we congregate in the bowels  of 
the ship,  in the stairwell by the car decks until a crew member lets us 
in and onto the coach again..

Coach starts and lurches forward,  expectantly paused on the ramp of the 
ferry,  our incipient coronary patient of a driver stalls the thing!  He 
manages to knock the intercom 'on', so we are treated to a resume of him 
trying to get out of the mess, keys jangle until we wonder just how many 
keys he brought with him, cries of 'Oh no!' (with worse ones kept out of 
reach no doubt?) - Very entertaining it is too,  but he eventually finds 
the  right  key  and  roars off the ramp  to  the  relief  of  everybody 
concerned.. Long way for an RAC patrolman to swim otherwise!

(Now 8.30 Central European Time - CET - all times given from now are CET 
unless stated otherwise..)

The  journey  proper  starts as we whisk  through  a  rapidly  darkening 
Calais,  the  video screens switch on and we are treated to nothing less 
than  Four  Weddings and a Funeral - with Danish subtitles!!!  Yes  even 
*that*  bit  at the beginning,  where Hugh 'suck me harder' Grant is  in 
full four letter word flow..  (More on that in the next realtime bit..)

'Four  Weddings' is a film that is remarkably good if you don't pay  too 
much close attention to it,  watching it in an abstract 'keeping up with 
the general flow' sort of way..  We pass all the way into Belgium,  some 
members of the party attempt a light doze,  Mr Pink being voted the best 
sleeper of the trip..

The film finishes, and we are booted off the coach for half an hour into 
the  crisp  night  air  whilst several of the  seats  are  converted  to 
sleeping  couchette  things,  and get to try out Belgian garage  toilets 
striding past the queue of waiting tooth-brushers..  Refreshed and drunk 
of  Belgian  garage water,  Felice and I spot the other members  of  the 
party sizing up a nearby clump of trees as a toilet facility..

Back on the coach,  discover that some of the seats grabbed for sleeping 
accomodation  are  ours,  so scramble for alternative place to park  our 
bottoms  on..  I end up next to Mike Noyce for the rest of the journey.. 
Serious  travelling  Hamburgward now ensues,  with several less  serious 
attempts  at  trying to sleep..  As is usual on coaches,  the seats have 
been  designed  for pixies which is hellishly uncomfortable  for  anyone 
bigger..  Trying  to  lean  back into the seat effectively  doubles  the 
pressure on your bottom which soon chafes and hurts.. Leaning forward is 
much better,  but comes with a risk of bashing your nose out on the hard 
plastic seat backing..  Maggie Editor hits on brilliant interim solution 
where  he takes detachable part of seat cover and rests head forward  on 
this..  It  is  still  not sleep as we know it Jim,  because as soon  as 
anything  like a dreamlike state starts to happen,  the coach lurches to 
remind you where you are, and you're back to square one again..

(DAY TWO..)

Anyway,  I  liked  to know where we were travelling,  noting the  border 
crossings for Holland and Germany..  Later,  about 2.30am on, a dramatic 
pick up in the quality of night time scenery is observed.. After passing 
through  the  German border area,  some of the most isolated  and  unlit 
areas yet, we pass into what was probably the Ruhr Valley heavy industry 
area,  with  some  stunning night time 'Bladerunner' pastiches of  heavy 
industry..  Maggie  editor  now wide awake and interested..  (Noting the 
existence  of  the little town of 'Wankum',  everyone had a  chuckle  at 
that, sad eh?)

Mike Noyce is also awake,  so it comes to pass that we have an impromptu 
picnic,   finishing   off  his  dried  up  chicken  and  tomato  ketchup 
sandwiches and mini Mars Bars.. Apart from odd sweets and countless cups 
of  coffee  taken  during the day,  this is the only food I  have  until 
6.00pm  that  evening..  Kev Davies sleeps on nearby,  but wakes up  and 
joins us,  and Felice noisily puts in an appearance as well.. All try to 
go back to sleep again, and more countless Autobahn miles slip by..

It  is  just starting to show the first traces of dawn  when  the  coach 
pulls into a service station, this is the last stop just before Hamburg, 
and  we  pile off the coach again,  stepping carefully over  the  liquid 
trail  of whatever that was spilling from the coach toilet  and  running 
down  into  the car park..  This service station has an all  night  cafe 
open,  so we pile in and order our first coffee on German soil..  Coffee 
is  too  kind a word,  as it is basically pure caffeine cut with just  a 
little  hot  water..  However,  it is just what is needed now..  The food 
seems  a  tad expensive (as with all service stations worldwide)  so  we 
leave that where it is..

6.30am..
 
Back on the coach again,  and finally we reach the Hamburg bus station.. 
Bags off, and into the crisp cold morning we set off to find the Central 
Railway  Station  (Haupt-Banhhof) which we do after five  minutes  brisk 
walk..  The next problem is one of killing time,  as the convention does 
not  open  until 12.00pm,  this leaves us with rather a lot of  time  in 
between.. Some initial wandering sets us down on one of the platforms of 
the  railway station,  sitting on some chairs made out of disused  radar 
dishes, which is a good point to pick up on the realtime article again..

