To  put a bit more explanatory flesh on the bare bones of  the  realtime 
article..  A  person of a drunk disposition approached our table in  the 
far  corner,  and  picked on Neil/Arnel,  the other German speaker apart 
from  Tat  in  our  group..  After some brandishing  of  a  (thankfully) 
sheathed  knife,  and  other vague threats that sober people  would  not 
understand, he wobbled away again.. Dead silence ruled during this tense 
time,  as  we  considered  whether  a  quick  overpowering/running  away 
manouvre  would  be  needed..  The  rest of this  bit  of  the  realtime 
perfectly sums up our time in the cafe.. Were we bored or what!

Time to catch a train then,  as Tat and Neil purchase group tickets that 
will  take  us  all the way to Harburg,  the nearest major stop  to  the 
party..Tat  phones one of the organisers,  it looks like that the  doors 
won't be open until the stroke of twelve, but we are on our way anyway.. 
The commuter train is straightforward,  and the journey to Harburg takes 
about ten minutes.. The journey from Harburg, to the party location at a 
place called Hittfeld proves less so..
 
A  very prolonged study of a map by the more  cartographically  inclined 
members of our party takes a ridiculously long time, but it is with some 
hope that we go above ground, and await the bus to Hittfeld..

We  theoretically  have a choice of conveyance to the  show,  either  an 
'hourly'  regular  service,  which  proved  anything but,  and  a  (Non-
appearing)  Shuttle bus laid on by the show organisers..  And that  just 
about sums up how our final leg travel arrangements to Symposium  went.. 
The anticipated time for the hourly bus came and went,  still sunny, but 
not  very  warm..  Tat goes off to try to contact one of the  organisers 
with  no result..  This person is not at home and presumably  organising 
things  (but  not a shuttle bus!) As the minutes  lengthen,  other  lost 
looking souls carry large quantities of baggage appear,  these also seem 
to be going to the Symposium, and we strike up a brief conversation with 
one  of the Amiga contingent,  firmly placing the blame for the bussless 
fiasco on the PC owners organising the thing..

Shortly  before  1.00pm,  our bus finally appears,the  regular  'hourly' 
service,  and a large mass of people pile on..  A nerve-stripping drive, 
no,  more  of  a slalom ride to Hittfeld follows..  Maggie Editor  finds 
himself  standing,  and  almost  having arms torn out  at  the  shoulder 
sockets as a result of drivers extravagant manouvering..

We  de-buss  at Hittfeld ten minutes later,  and a brief walk through  a 
very  sleepy  looking but well-kept village brings us to  the  Symposium 
venue which is based in some function rooms hired from a rather well-to-
do looking restaurant..

 ++The Party!!++

At last we come into contact with the reason for being here,  as several 
official looking people in pinky/purple tee-shirts rush around, take our 
35DM  off  us for the three days entry fee,  and clip a small  piece  of 
unremovable  plastic to our belts..  We seek the Atari area which is not 
hard  to find,  filled with the bodies and hardware of dozens of  Falcon 
owners,  with  the  odd bit or two of other hardware dotted  around  the 
place..  As  the  'UK scene',  we have our own table allocated,  which is 
just about adequate for Tat and his Falcon,  Leon, a small angora rabbit 
named Cyril,  and not a lot else.. Next to us is Arto, a French dude who 
is  singlehandledly  representing the might of the French scene  as  the 
author  of  a new Hydroxid demo,  with whom a quite profitable  creative 
relationship  is struck up with Tat and Leon over the next few days..  A 
bit further on,  the Hungarian contingent,  opposite and down a bit, the 
megamighty Lazer in a corner..

I  glance  around  and end up talking to an  unknown  German  ST  coder, 
hanging around with the group Therapy, with virtually the only ST in the 
room,  who  is  showing off a new demo which does not need one of  those 
fancy Falcon things to work.. Indeed such things as 25 frames per second 
scaling  and rotating,  and even decent texture mapping are shown on the 
humble 'FM.. This unknown fellow is one of the truly dedicated coders at 
the show,  as he showed no sign of stopping, literally crashing out onto 
the keyboard of his computer in the later stages (and he was not he only 
one to do that, eh Tat!)

(Who are you chap! If you are reading this, and know who you are, get in 
touch with us! - CiH)

Part  of the early reconnaissance finds DBA at the near end of the  room 
who  are  literally  typing the first syllables of  the  DBA  real  time 
article,  having got as far as putting the words 'DBA REAL TIME ARTICLE' 
on the screen..  I meet Slimer and look at him,  decide he is very tall, 
and he invites me to kick off the real time article,  which I do.. Other 
people  from  the Maggie Team are soon on there as well,  so it is  some 
time before any other attending humanoids get to put a key in edgeways..

Going  away for a little while,  I retreat to the suspiciously clean and 
peaceful  toilets,  having  a  wash/shit/shave and getting a  change  of 
clothes.  I  feel quite a bit better although the food arrangements  are 
disappointing,  that is,  nothing ready until 6.00pm,  so the stomach is 
tightened  another notch or eight,  but at least a handy coke machine is 
there  and satisfies the thirst/quick cheap burst of false  energy  need 
for 2DM a go.. 

A  further  look  arond the room results in a  sighting  of  the  newest 
version of 'Doomino', the promising Doom-like 3-D texture map engine for 
the Falcon initially shown as a 96k intro last year at Fried Bits.. What 
'Doomino' has become is the nearly complete commercial release 'Running' 
with  a  much  tidier looking and more  optimised  game  engine,  decent 
looking game status panels,  a gun on screen,  and real bad guys!! (Also 
later on,  we saw a really nifty Psygnosis-like rendered intro sequence, 
but we won't hold that against you!) I take the opportunity to introduce 
the  good people of Stax to Maggie 19,  which they quite enjoy (I hope!) 
They say that 'Running' should be ready inside six months..

(Typically, a preview version of this game is only released at 3.00am in 
the morning after we had set off back home..)  :-(

I also get to see in these opening hours;

'Skyfall'  finally working as a fully finished (almost)  game..  Version 
0.96 is released for the Symposium..  Quite an improvement from the very 
early  version  that was briefly shown at the Atari World Xmas  Show  in 
December..  Skyfall also counts as *the* major distraction  from getting 
serious  stuff like this show report done,  and playing of this game has 
had to be severly rationed!!

'Atari  Dream  Machine',  probably  the best 'serious'  German  language 
diskmag with their latest issue, number six, released here.. From what I 
could  grasp of it,  quite up to date and well written..  Talking to the 
editor shows him to be fully aware of Maggie 19 to the extent of  having 
a copy on his hard disk..  Also a major revamp of the menu shell for the 
next issue is imminent as well..

A Jaguar developers kit running some mutant version of the virtual light 
machine, with some very wild plasma shock effects..

Several  of  Tat's new 3-D routines,  shortly to make their way  into  a 
combined  Avena/Digital Chaos demo..  These are very very nice too,  and 
several very movie-like in a 2001 a Space Oddity sort of way! 

More  of  the DBA realtime article,  which Maggie Team input  tended  to 
dominate a lot of..

Lots  and lots of Falcons in huge full size tower cases,  with masses of 
accelerator cards and stuff.. After a while, we did not notice anymore..

Lots  of  people  also  using a 640 x 200 style  desktop  on  their  RGB 
monitors, relieved to see I'm not the only one!!

I Also said hello to the Scandinavian representatives, NoCrew..

Felice gets his camcorder out to start recording people in various poses 
of desperation.. He also recorded a fair bit of what went on in the main 
hall too,  I now have a copy of the tape!  Watch out for screen grabs in 
