6.00pm or 18.00h CET, and D-PLUS 1.5777 seconds..
Time passes in that effortless Catherine de Medici nibbling absently  at 
the corner of a mousemat manner,  which it likes to do..  We sight signs 
of life in the eating pit,  or rather,  the serving food to the starving 
masses  pit,  as  various pizza preparing persons bestir  themselves  to 
frenzied  cooking  type activity..  Which means that three innocent  and 
unfortunate  Amiga owners who GOT IN MY WAY are killed in the  rush..  I 
order pizza twice,  or zwei to be really accurate,  to go (to the nearby 
unoccupied  tables)  and eat,  a joining in of the rest of the  visiting 
party follows as I stuff, chew and generally cram my stomach.. The pizza 
is  moderately ok,  which translates to absolutely the best thing I have 
ever eaten in my foodless since 2.30am previously state..

I go back for thirds..

The rest of the first evening passes quietly enough as we settle down to 
an  ordered routine,  people who can code getting intermittent space  on 
Tat's Falcon, the rest of us pacing around the show.. About this time, I 
notice  that  there  are Commodore 64's in quite large  numbers  at  the 
show..  Several  of these machines have a suspicious bank of switches on 
the  top,  and I discover that these are the toggles for such things  as 
new issue ROMs,  boosted up (20mhz!) processors,  extra (256K) memory, 1 
GB  hard drives and more??  As it is they are still capable of producing 
some  spiffy effects on their own,  with one machine running a digitised 
looping  film  sequence  from Terminator that went  on  for  some  time, 
another  running  a  flaming vector effect  (according  to  Tat,  *very* 
difficult to do on a C64!) At a gathering at the Dutch end of the  room, 
I see Sentry's Commodore 128 running a Wolfenstein style texture  mapped 
dungeon..  A  listing  for the event had about thirty crews for the  C64 
attending,  and it is amazing that this machine should still have such a 
big following after all this time,  and gives hope to the rest of us who 
still prefer to work on non "commercial" formats..

Other  things that are done that evening include a further visit to  the 
Dutch section where there is more clowning around done on their realtime 
article.  They  are  also up to some traditional Dutch Fried  Bits  type 
