Hmmmmm...

Just  about the last thing that we do that day,  is to attend the  laser 
show  which  is running in the main hall shortly before  midnight..  All 
thoughts of sleep banished for the moment,  we settle down as the public 
address  system requests all the monitors and sound systems in the  main 
hall be turned off,  an expectant hush falls over the hall, as the first 
part  of a 'kicking' soundtrack starts up,  with the promise of  lengthy 
and  spectacular light pictures all over the hall..  About five  minutes 
later, it all shudders to a stop, and that is really it.. Several people 
sardonically take it as eloquent commentary on the state of organisation 
of the event as the PC,  Amiga, and C64 sponsored burble starts up again 
in  the  main hall..  We (non coding) members of the UK  visiting  party 
decide to call it a (very long) day and find a place to kip..

The  'sleeping  room',  seems  to be a ad-hoc adaptation of one  of  the 
unused  computing  rooms,  tables  and some chairs abound..  We clear  a 
space,  trying not to disturb the few people already in there and settle 
our  sleeping  equipment into position..  I inflate my airbed  with  the 
footpump, Felice goes for his sleeping bag, and so does Mike Noyce.. Kev 
Davies reaches for the floor, and is happy with that..

DAY THREE..

Time passed ever so s-l-o-w-l-y..

The airbed is surprisingly very comfortable..  Sleep comes quite easily, 
or  at  least it does,  once the procession of people moving  into,  and 
through  the  room,  also seeking a place to rest,  stops a couple or so 
hours later,  and I sleep,  very,  very deeply,  until about 8am or soon 
after,  when a distinct chill in the air wakes me up..  Even then I only 
rise  up  very slowly and make my way to the toilets to indulge  in  the 
usual shit/shave/wash routine..

For  some  reason known only to German speakers,  the gents toilets  are 
closed  (something to do with cleaning them??) So I find myself  sharing 
the  little  girls room with some unidentified females who  are  washing 
their hair in the sinks.. This does not complicate matters though, and I 
am soon ready to return to the Atari room related fray..

Not too much is going on,  Kev Davies, and Neil are also up at about the 
same  time,  Mike Noyce is still asleep,  and Leon has bedded down in an 
obscure  corner  of the hall,  and after his display of lateness on  the 
realtime article,  he is deservedly asleep..  Tat has slept where he has 
fallen,  on  his  Falcon..  The Maggie pen and paper realtime article is 
trapped under his head.. Slimer and the DBA team are also sort of awake, 
Slimer  not  too happy having had very little sleep in  the  night..  As 
people collect themselves together,  me, Neil and Kev decide to go for a 
little walk around the metropolis of Hittfeld..  The word 'breakfast' is 
not  spoken  by any of us,  but at the top of my mind at least,  as  the 
rather limited food facilities do not do anything until noon..

After  a  wander  in the grey chill morning air,  the  word  'breakfast' 
managed  to  remain unspoken,  as we returned to base  hungry..  Several 
Symposium goers laden down with paper carrier bags return from the local 
supermarket, which seems like a really good place to go next..

Collecting the remaining members of the UK party, now that Felice, Mike, 
Leon  and  Tat have joined us,  we set out again for the supermarket  as 
food is now definitely on the 'things to do' list..  The idea is to fill 
up  with crisps and drink and related junk,  to reduce our dependence on 
the pricey pizza concession..  Tat,  Leon, Kev and Mike head off for the 
supermarket.. Myself, Neil, and Felice take in a nearby cafe..

The cafe is small,  pleasantly appointed, and part of a rural scene that 
only expects about three exciting things a year to happen..  Our arrival 
seems  to  add  a  fourth  to that list,  as  we  order  various  exotic 
combinations of coffee and hot chocolate..  Unlike the Hamburg cafe, no-
one  appears to brandish a slicing implement at us,  and dare I say  it, 
the natives were pleasant!

Having  topped up caffeine levels nicely,  we go to join the rest at the 
bulging mini-mart..

The supermarket is very crowded with Saturday morning shoppers,  part of 
that  is  due  to  the  weight of  extra  Symposium  customers  such  as 
ourselves.. A lot of it is also due to the Teutonic keenness on Saturday 
half-day  closing,  and  Sunday  closing..  No walking to the 'open  all 
hours'  place  up  the road here..  We find the others,  and load up  on 
crisps, bacon snacks, (weak) orange drink, Coke, peanuts, tortilla chips 
KitKats,  and  more..  We steer clear of German Mars Bars which are two-
thirds scale models of proper Mars Bars,  and twice as expensive..  Some 
members  of the party take up baguette type things which turn out to  be 
part-baked  bread,  delicious  if finished off in a hot oven for ten  or 
fifteen  minutes and eaten with garlic butter whilst still  hot..  Tough 
going if not baked for for that sort of time before consumption, in fact 
rather  rubbery in texture,  and there was no oven amongst the toasters, 
coffee machines, waffle makers and prototype nuclear reactors fixed into 
tower cases found at the Symposium.. Still, nobody minded..

We  get  back and settle down and the sound of contented  crunching  and 
rustling noises rises from our bit of the hall shortly after..  A little 
while after that sees us sitting back in the Atari room opposite  Slimer 
and  XTC-1  of  Sentry  who  are  unenthusiatically  slapping  breakfast 
together..  About  this  time,  the  realtime article makes  an  overdue 
reappearance..

